<h2> Studies & interests in his field: </h2>
<p1>Ibn an Nafis was highly passionate about medicine with a focus on anatomy, physiology, and cardiology. He spent some time delving into the complexities of the human body and its operations. His well-known work "Sharh Tashrih Al Qanun" (a commentary on anatomy found in Avicenna's Canon) delves far into deconstructing and clarifying anatomy's intricacies. 
Ibn An Nafis was interested in the system where he carried out in-depth study and made several ground-breaking discoveries that contradicted established theories based on Galen's writings. </p>

<p1>Beyond his efforts, his ground-breaking discoveries on blood circulation highlight the roles that the heart and the pulmonary circulation play. He also became quite passionate in physiological studies. He nailed annotations to books and led thoughtful conversations about theology by fusing his expertise with philosophical ideas. </p>

<p1>Ibn An Nafis Exemplified a holistic approach to understanding the world around him in essence, his scholarly pursuits in composed, a spectrum, ranging from medicine, anatomy, physiology, and cardiology to theology and philosophy. He made contributions to the field of medicine through his interests and comprehensive studies leaving a lasting impression on medical knowledge during his era. </p>

<h3><h3>
<img src= https://muslimheritage.com/sites/default/files/pulmonary0.jpg width="1400", height="500" = ibn-an-nafis 
<h3></h3>

<h2> Contributions </h2>
<p1>Through his groundbreaking work in medicine, Ibn Al Nafis made contributions to society and the Muslim world. His understanding of the circulatory system was a noteworthy accomplishment since it refuted preexisting notions and provided a more accurate picture of blood circulation. </p>

<p>For years, medical education and practice were influenced by the descriptions and treatment methods provided in his books, including "Sharh Tashrih al Qanun." He led pupils in his role as a teacher. played a major part in the dissemination of medical knowledge throughout the Muslim world. Translations of his writings into other languages served to advance medical knowledge throughout Europe and foster exchange.</p>

<p1>Ibn Al-Nafis's contributions to medicine are still being made, and his stature in the Muslim community and in history has made him a hero.</p>

<h3 style="color:blue;">Sharh Al-Qanun</h3>
<img src= https://alchetron.com/cdn/ibn-al-nafis-0e83e628-7140-46ae-a2e9-dc19c5b3165-resize-750.jpeg width="1400", height="500" = ibn-an-nafis 
<h3></h3>

<h2> His Active Years</h2>
<p1>Ibn al Nafis, an astonishingly known figure in the history of medicine, was active during the years 1236 to 1277. He started his career at Al Nassri Hospital in 1236. Later transitioned to Al Mansouri Hospital eventually attaining the title of "Chief of Physicians." At the age of 29 in 1242 he gained acclaim for his work on Anatomy in Avicenna's Canon. Subsequently he worked on The Comprehensive Book on Medicine between 1243 and 1244 CE when he was 31 years old. Notably from 1260, to 1277 Ibn al Nafis served as the doctor of Sultan Baibars further establishing his legacy in the field.

